    "updated_at": "2015-04-14T16:07:06Z",
    "body": "> To me it seems like actually encoding this in a source file is an antipattern? For example how can you guarantee that the library will be at the same location on all systems you're compiling on?\n\nSure, a source-file with full path to library shouldn't be distributed. I perfectly understand this point. But here it is more to have a possibility to mitigated a packaging problem.\n\nI think using a separated `kind` would help here\u00a0: it should be possible, from the command-line, to pass `-l filepath=/path/to/my/liblibrary.so.X.Y` instead of `-l library`.\n\nBut it don't permit to fully disambiguate a `#[link(name=\"library\")]` using command-line: the link resolv the dependencies in order, and it seems `#[link(name=\"library\")]` is passed before `-l filepath=/path/to/my/liblibrary.so.X.Y` on linker args. (not sure to be clear...)\n",
