    "created_at": "2015-04-14T18:47:21Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-04-14T18:48:22Z",
    "body": "This passes the name directly to the linker unconditionally. Before doing something like this I would want to know what the semantics are for passing dylibs, static libs, rlibs, other random types of files, on all platforms. Can this be supported on Windows, with the gnu linker and the microsoft linker?\n\nI would want tests that cover all these cases. Linkers are very futzy and behave inconsistently across platforms. It's important that Rust deal with them in a way that can be supported - we've had no end of trouble with linker interaction so we need to be careful not to make any new messes.\n\nAre there other, possibly more standard, ways to solve #24345, for instance by passing the revision of the .so to the linker?\n",
