    "created_at": "2015-04-15T04:54:21Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-04-15T04:54:21Z",
    "body": "> This passes the name directly to the linker unconditionally. Before doing something like this I would want to know what the semantics are for passing dylibs, static libs, rlibs, other random types of files, on all platforms.\n\nyes. it is the way to specify which version of dylib to use for the linker. I am not sure that it would be possible to restrict the type of file is passed (if it is a dylib, a static lib or something else): it would involve to have the ability to check the type of file is passed (and will introduce a race between type-check and file passing).\n\nand yes, it open also a way to abuse the linker (passing arbitrary arguments). Maybe I could check if the argument is a file first.\n\nabout permit it on all platforms, yes it could be more fine checked by allowing that only for some platforms.\n\n> I would want tests that cover all these cases.\n\nI could try to provide a test for that.\n\n> Are there other, possibly more standard, ways to solve #24345, for instance by passing the revision of the .so to the linker?\n\nsome versions of `g++` linker can permit an alternate way: `-l:liblibray.so.X.Y` (according to http://stackoverflow.com/questions/3384897/how-to-link-a-specific-version-of-a-shared-library-in-makefile-without-using-ld).\n\nanother way could be to make a directory with only the desired so version, and link to it with `-L my-directory-with-only-desired-so`. I will check this possibility: it could permit to solve #24345 to packaging level.\n",
